CI/CD with GitHub

5 steps

In the previous tutorial, you learned how to use GitHub and GitHub Desktop to configure branch protection rules to create a development workflow involving pull requests and merge commits for a single product page with static HTML, CSS and Javascript. In this tutorial, you will be using GitHub Actions to add CI/CD to your workflow to run a Python file upon successful pull requests as a foundation to using GitHub Actions for more complex use cases.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • There are no pre-requisites

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Use GitHub Actions to add CI/CD to your workflow
  • Configure a workflow that runs a Python file upon successful pull requests

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: Introduction to CI/CD

    CI/CD stands for Continuous Integration, Continuous Delivery and Continuous Deployment. This means implementing automation into the different stages of development, through testing, with the objective of delivering apps to customers quickly and with improvements made incrementally, based on customer feedback.

    You can read more about CI/CD below.

     What is CI/CD?

    In this tutorial, imagine that your development team plans to use Pythons FastAPI to deploy a dynamic web application for the restaurant. With the end goal being to implement a CI/CD pipeline that would automatically run and deploy the web application through a Python file, you have been tasked to create a basic pipeline that would first run a simple Python script.

  • Step 2: Adding a Python File To Your Repository

    Using the same repository you created in the previous tutorial, create a python file named main.py in the root folder of your repository. The file should contain the following code.

    print(Hello world :D)
    Python

    Then, using GitHub Desktop, commit and push the file into the main branch of the repository. You may directly push to the main branch, or push to the development branch and create a pull request, similar to what you did in the previous tutorial.

  • Step 3: Configuring GitHub Actions

    Now that you have a Python file in the repository, its time to create a workflow for it to run automatically. In development, code and configuration files have an expected outcome, workflows can help developers test out their configurations and code, and even send new code straight to production to be hosted. Head over to https://github.com/YourGitHubUsername/Username-Git-Shop/actions, replacing YourGitHubUsername with your GitHub Username.

    In the Actions panel on the left-hand side of the page, click New Workflow.

    Next, search Python in the search workflows field and select the workflow named Python application. This will provide you with a .yml file, which is a template for installing dependencies and running tests and lint whenever pull requests are made or the repository is pushed to.

    For now, commit the template file by clicking the Start commit button, then the Commit new file button.

    Since you committed and pushed the template file, the workflow was executed. You may view the log by viewing the Actions tab, clicking on the Python application workflow, selecting the Create python-app.yml workflow and clicking the Build button. Do not mind any errors that may be shown.

  • Step 4: Configuring Your Workflow

    Currently, the workflow runs the pytest command from the pytest package, not our file, every time a pull request is made or the repository is pushed to. We want to configure it to run our python file main.py only when a pull request is successfully merged, which is similar to a push. We will edit some of the template file we previously created at /.github/workflows/python-app.yml to achieve this.

    To do this, go to the Code tab of your Username-Git-Shop repository. Click on the .github/workflows folder, then click python-app.yml. You should see a file that looks something like the screenshot below.

    Next, find the following lines in the code.

    name: Test with pytest
    run: |
     pytest

    Edit this portion of the template file to run main.py instead of pytest by doing the following:

    1. Edit the name section to read Run main.
    2. Edit the run section to read python main.py
  • Step 5: Running Your Workflow

    If you had correctly edited the template file in Step 3, your workflow should now be working. Edit the Python file main.py, changing it to the following. 

    print(Hello Username :D)
    Python

    IMPORTANT: Remember to replace all instances of "Username" in the code with your own username!

    Then, commit and push the changes to the development branch, make a pull request to the main branch, and merge it like you did in the previous tutorial. After merging successfully, you should be able to see the logs for your workflow in the Actions tab on GitHub.

    Open the step that ran your Python file and screenshot the entire workflow log of your merged pull request to complete this step! Make sure you include the entire workflow in the screenshot, which must be of your whole screen. Check the expected output if you are not sure what you should include in your screenshot.

    With the completion of all of the steps, you have set up a basic CI/CD pipeline that runs a predefined Python file upon successful merging of pull requests. This makes it easier for your development team to keep track of changes and ensure that the main branch that gets deployed is protected!

    Your configurations also set up the foundation for creating more complex pipelines that can connect to various cloud providers and assist with automatically deploying web applications on their Virtual Machine instances.
